      passage: `The Paradox of Democratic Populism

Populism presents liberal democracies with a paradox. On one hand, populist movements often articulate real grievances: the perception that established institutions serve narrow elites rather than ordinary citizens, that professional politicians are insulated from the consequences of their decisions, and that the voices of ordinary people are systematically ignored. These are not trivial complaints.

On the other hand, the solutions that populist leaders tend to offer are — almost by definition — incompatible with the complex realities of modern governance. Populism thrives on simplicity: the identification of an enemy (elites, immigrants, foreign powers), the claim that the solution is obvious and is being suppressed by those in power, and the assertion that only one leader or movement genuinely represents "the people."

What makes this paradox so difficult to resolve is that responding to populism with technocratic dismissal often makes it worse. When established politicians and commentators treat populist voters as simply ignorant or misled, they reinforce the very sense of condescension and exclusion that drives populist sentiment in the first place.

The most serious scholarship on this subject suggests that effective responses to populism must simultaneously address its legitimate concerns — through more inclusive institutions, greater accountability, and genuine efforts to reduce inequality — whilst resisting its authoritarian tendencies. This is difficult. It requires holding two things in mind at once: that populist voters are not wrong to feel that something has gone wrong, and that the solutions offered by populist leaders are frequently dangerous.`,
