      context: 'محاضرة في علم النفس التطبيقي',
      text: 'What the research consistently demonstrates is that people are not irrational — they are predictably irrational. Cognitive biases such as loss aversion and confirmation bias do not vary randomly from person to person; they are consistent features of human cognition. It has been found, for example, that a potential loss of one hundred pounds motivates behaviour roughly twice as strongly as an equivalent gain. This is attributable to our evolutionary history, in which avoiding danger was more pressing than pursuing opportunity. The implications for policy design are significant: if we want to change behaviour, we need to change the environment in which decisions are made, not simply inform people and hope they act rationally.',
