      text: 'What I want you to take away is that the four principles of medical ethics — beneficence, non-maleficence, autonomy, and justice — are not a decision-making algorithm. They are a vocabulary for articulating the ethical dimensions of clinical decisions. It has been argued that autonomy has become too dominant in contemporary bioethics at the expense of beneficence. There are legitimate grounds for this concern. That said, the alternative — a return to paternalistic medicine in which doctors decide what is best for patients without consulting them — would represent a serious ethical regression. Balancing these principles requires exactly the kind of contextual judgment that cannot be reduced to rules.',
